{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17479037","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17479037"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:19:47+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:19:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19191"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"19191","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/19191"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.83,0.03,0.05,0.01,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11925"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92796"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11925","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11925"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19191"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76155"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1383"},{"type":"tags","id":"1664"},{"type":"tags","id":"8904"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"27943"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31827"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92796","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/92796"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA three-year-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with his parent after developing a white reflex in his right eye over the past two weeks. His parent also reports that the eye appears to be turning inward. He was born at term and has no significant medical history. He takes no regular medications and his immunisations are up to date.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is a white pupillary reflex (leukocoria) in the right eye and convergent strabismus. Red reflex testing shows an abnormal reflex on the right.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Retinoblastoma","Retinal detachment","Coats disease","Persistent hyperplastic primary vitreous","Congenital cataract"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis child presents with leukocoria (white pupillary reflex) and new onset strabismus, which are concerning signs that require urgent evaluation. Given the age of presentation and the combination of findings, \u003Cstrong\u003Eretinoblastoma\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely diagnosis. Retinoblastoma is the most common primary intraocular malignancy of childhood, typically presenting between one and three years of age.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERetinal detachment\u003C/strong\u003E can cause leukocoria but is less common as a primary condition in children of this age without predisposing factors such as trauma or retinopathy of prematurity. However, it can occur secondary to retinoblastoma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECoats disease\u003C/strong\u003E is a rare condition characterised by abnormal development of retinal blood vessels. While it can cause leukocoria, it typically affects males unilaterally and presents slightly later in childhood (average age 8-16 years).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPersistent hyperplastic primary vitreous\u003C/strong\u003E is a congenital condition that usually presents in early infancy, not at age three years. It is typically unilateral and associated with a small eye (microphthalmia).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECongenital cataract\u003C/strong\u003E would typically be noticed earlier in life, either at birth or in early infancy. The late presentation at age three years makes this diagnosis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe combination of new onset strabismus and leukocoria in a previously well three-year-old child should raise immediate concern for retinoblastoma. This condition requires urgent ophthalmology assessment as it is potentially life-threatening if not treated promptly. Early diagnosis and treatment are essential for both vision and life preservation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Retinoblastoma is the most common primary intraocular malignancy in children, typically presenting between ages 1-3 years.","Leukocoria (white pupillary reflex) and strabismus are common presenting signs of retinoblastoma.","Early diagnosis and treatment of retinoblastoma are essential for both vision preservation and survival."],"references":["Kliegman RM, St. Geme JW, Blum NJ, Shah SS, Tasker RC, Wilson KM, editors. Disorders of the eye. In: Nelson Textbook of Pediatrics. 21st ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76155"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19191"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76155","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/76155"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-19T13:04:19+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-19T13:04:56+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11925"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92796"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"se